WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:23.000
This is Tuesday, the 24th of May, 2011. My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Bowl History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:41.000
I'm in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma with filmmaker John Bishop. We are here for the joint project of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian's National Museum of African-American History and Culture for an oral history series called the Civil Rights History Project.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:46.000
We are here for a title called the Civil Rights History Project.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Let's say it. Thank you.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:50.000
I'm sorry.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:01:09.000
We're just easing into a first and what will be two sessions this afternoon, one with Miss Marilyn (née Calvin) Luper Hildreth, for surname that birth, of course, is Luper, and Marilyn (née Calvin) Luper Hildreth.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Thank you so much for welcoming us to Oklahoma City. It's a real honor and pleasure to be with you. Thank you for coming.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:31.000
We're interested, obviously, to hear really about your to begin, about your mother. Of course, we'll want to hear much from you about your own experience directly.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:37.000
That's you were right in the middle of all of what happened in the late 50s, early 60s here in Oklahoma City.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:41.000
Could I ask you just to talk a little bit to begin about your mother?

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.000
I'd love to. That's a good starting point.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:58.000
My mother has been an educator most of her life. She had an opportunity to teach at Dunjee High School, which is in Spencer, Oklahoma.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:09.000
Some of us call the country. Young people that have never ever had any opportunities to see anything with their immediate environments.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Mom wrote a play called Martin Luther King Jr, Martin Luther King Jr, and the young people Dengie were able to wrote it and they produced the play.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:41.000
A guy by the name of Herbert L. Wright with the NAACP was here in Oklahoma City and solvah play and invited the group of young people to the NAACP National Convention to produce Martin Luther King Jr.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Oh, everyone was so excited, but by her being a history teacher, she decided to give us a lesson in history.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:03:12.000
Before Martin Luther King Jr, if you could walk with me through the streets of Oklahoma City during that period of time, we could go downtown in downtown Oklahoma City and shop in an store where you could not try on a hat.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:27.000
You could not try on shoes. When my grandmother went to buy me shoes, she had to take some three-it and tie a knot in it to determine the size shoe that she would buy for me to wear.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:36.000
You could not eat in any restaurant. You would have to go to the back of the restaurants and they would pass you a brown bag.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:48.000
Come on and keep walking with me in Oklahoma City. We could not live [south of] NE 7th Street in Oklahoma City.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:04:02.000
We could not use the same telephone booths - one was [white] one was 'colored. We could not even drink out of the same water fountain and I could continue on and on.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:19.000
But I just wanted to feel where we were coming from in this period of time. So the advisors and young people that were involved in Martin Luther King Jr got together and said, OK, mom said, I'm going to do what I'm going to do.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:37.000
We're going to go to the Northern route + Southern route - the canonical 1957 NAACP tour journey and we're going to come back to southern route. Everybody was so excited and when that trip started and we started to New York City, something happened for the first time in our lives.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:50.000
We were able to go and sit down and drink a coke in a restaurant. We were able to go in and say restaurant is everybody else and eat a hamburger.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:05:04.000
We were even able to drink out of the same water fountain as other folks. Oh, we've never seen anything like this because 100% of the people on that trip, the young people, had never been out of Oklahoma.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:23.000
So we thought that that's the way it was supposed to be in Oklahoma and the United States of America. Oh, we went to New York and we had a wonderful time. The experiences and being able to tour all the great historical monuments there.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:41.000
You were about 11 years old. No, I was younger. I was younger. So what happened was, when I way back, we came back to the southern route and faced the age of discrimination.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:51.000
The same thing that we thought that we had to go through and found that we didn't. We were slapped in the face whatever you had.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:06:10.000
They used to tell us that a little bit of freedom is a dangerous thing. So when we came back to Oklahoma City, we were all ready to go because we had had that taste of freedom.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:22.000
And we started negotiating with the restaurants here in Oklahoma City and they told us that they didn't want to deal with us.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:27.000
And it kept going on and on and it seemed like forever to me.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:41.000
And one Monday night at our house at 1819 N.E. Park Place, we were having an NAACP Youth Council meeting. And I was eight years old at that time. This I can remember that I was not at 10 years old.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:54.000
And we were talking about our experiences and our negotiation. And I suggested made a motion that we would go down to Katz Drug Store store and just sit.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:08.000
Just sit and sit until they served us. Needless to say, a lot of people were not happy about it. And as a matter of fact, there were actually some of them were really mean to us.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:18.000
They were spit on us. They were kick us. They were call us names. They were telling they could go home.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:32.000
But they didn't deter us. And most of the young people, the canonical 13 original OKC Katz Drug Store sit-in participants were young people. And we didn't know fear, as fear like we know now.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:41.000
We thought we were on a job and on a mission and something that we had to do. So we continued to go back and we continued to sit in.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:52.000
And as you know, we went from restaurant to restaurant to restaurant until the walls of segregation started falling down in Oklahoma City.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:55.000
And so many interesting things happen.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:59.000
I want to ask you, for example, Katz Drug Store.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:06.000
Katz Drug Store. Katz Drug Store, desegregates its lunch counter in a couple of days.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
Yes.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
A couple other businesses do the same.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:11.000
Yes.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:12.000
Fairly quick order.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:13.000
Yes.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:14.000
How did that feel?

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:23.000
What did that suggest to you about your activism and its prospects?

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
That the walls came tumbling down.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:32.000
We were on a mission. And the mission would not be complete. It was like a strategy during the war.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:43.000
That mission would not be complete until every restaurant in Oklahoma City would allow people of color and would not discriminate because of the fact that the walls were completely covered in water.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:46.000
And the fact that they were black.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:55.000
Your mother as a leader of this group, I think that who is the approximate age range of those 13 children that first knighted Katz Drug Store?

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.000
ages six to about 16?

00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:59.000
A six about 16, yeah.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:10.000
Your mother would become such a focal point and such a leader across the next six years in all of the protest activity, all the direct action.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:24.000
And I'm interested too when you're thoughts about her as a woman in that role of leadership because of course most of the local hierarchy of every other sort would have been male.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.000
At that particular time, I did not look at it like that.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:37.000
My mother came from a very interesting family. Her father was a dreamer and my mother was a dreamer.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:51.000
My mother was a reader and educator. And she believed that we as a race of people could not advance unless we were educationally equipped.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:10:00.000
That's a laugh because a lot of kids would get a lot of toys for Christmas. We would get books.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:09.000
It's something she believed in and when she believed in something strong enough, she would go to the end of the world for her.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:20.000
And I often wondered, I often wondered where she got her strength from because for me to sit here and tell you it was easy for her.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:27.000
They tried to fire from the school system. People in the white community hated it.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:33.000
People in the black community did not want to be associated with it. It was not easy during that time.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:36.000
How did she hang out to her job?

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:42.000
God. As a matter of fact, days of them you don't know.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:52.000
They had a teacher in the Dunjee High School School system to promote him to be principal and he could become principal.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:11:04.000
Only job he had to do was fire Clara Luper. That's the only thing he had to do in order to become principal. He did not do it.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:15.000
And as the history you look back over the time, the roads that she's come. It was hard. It was difficult.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:21.000
One thing about it that I just love to death. You could knock it down but you could not keep it down.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:33.000
And coming she would tell the kids and she would prepare us to participate in the city and movement by teaching us the non-violent movement.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:41.000
The social change, what could happen if we would do this and we would do that. We could not win with violence.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:50.000
Every morning we had the same lesson. She would tell us if you did not tough enough, go to the hardware store and buy you some tough skin and get tough.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:59.000
Because life is not fair. You must be prepared and you must continue to fight. That's what she taught us. She taught us by Mahatma Mahatma Gandhi and the non-violent movement.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:06.000
We had to learn the steps. We had to learn how to be free.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
So...

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:42.000
I'm just wondering if you can talk a little bit about your mother's...

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:49.000
kind of who she was organically and how that related to the role that she played as an activist.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:57.000
My mother came from a place called Hoffman, Oklahoma.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:07.000
She would always say that she was topping her class. She was in the top five of her class but it was only five students in her class.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:17.000
She did not have the same textbooks in Hoffman as they had in other schools. They had the leftover books.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:27.000
So she would tell me when they would start reading the story and get to page 9. If my pages were to start again at page 21.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:37.000
And for years and years I asked myself, where did my mom get that toughness? How could she keep on ticking? No matter what.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:44.000
I've seen her in the adversity she's went through. But then I started thinking, really thinking.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:51.000
I thought about her father. I thought about her mother. I thought about her brother.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:14:00.000
The dad because he was not allowed to be treated in the hospital only because he was black.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:08.000
I think that that was the basic foundation in the strong belief in God that gave her that added strength.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:15.000
Because what she would say would happen to my brother, no child deserves that.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:24.000
So she continued and she fought with injustice as long as she could. She's still fighting. She's still hanging on.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:36.000
But I'm going to tell you something. I think that during this whole crisis I've only seen my mother face fear once that I can remember.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:42.000
I know there must have been many times but the time that impacted me the most.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:52.000
We were coming home from a freedom rally. And we had over 80 cars. You know, because all the kids were on our car you can look at and see the ground a lot of times.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:58.000
But we rode anywhere and hold car full of people all the time. And we were coming home from this rally.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:05.000
And we noticed that a group of white guys, men, were behind us in an old pickup truck.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:14.000
And I thought that they were just going to pass us or whatever, but they didn't.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:23.000
And the closer that we would get to home our destination, the closer they would follow us.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:33.000
So the spokesperson for the NAACP Youth Council is a young lady who's now a Barbara Posey Jones - University of Georgia professor.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:40.000
My name is Barbara Posey Jones - University of Georgia professor. And her father was a big man. And when I say big, he was a big man.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:48.000
And mom said, told us, Tokyo and then I said, these people are following us.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:16:04.000
And this is what I want you to do. When I turn this corner on N.E. 14th Street, I'll be blowing my horn and I want you to run up to the poses and knock on that door as hard as you can.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:10.000
I don't know what these guys want, but whatever they want, it's not right. Now do you understand me?

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:20.000
Don't say anything, but do exactly what I tell you to do. Open that door. I'm going to drive up there as close to the steps as I can get and run and knock that door down.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:34.000
And that's what we did. But when we did that, and they let us into the house, my mother drove away.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:43.000
I think that that's one of the greatest fears that I've ever had because my thought was, well, let's see my mom again.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:17:00.000
Is it worth it that my mother would not come back to us? Every time I think about that, I just say thank you God for the experience and thank you for letting my mom come back home to us.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:09.000
I want to ask about, how about, ask about your mom's relationship with a couple of different folks?

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:14.000
One is your family, your members of which church?

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
Fifth Street Baptist.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:24.000
Exactly. And can you talk about your mother's relationship with your pastor and the community of the network of black pastors in the city?

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:37.000
She was loved by some. She was feared by some and disliked by some. That's just the way it was.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:40.000
The reasons were fear.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:48.000
We met in the churches that we would meet at many of them were threatened.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:57.000
The other congregation didn't want us there because they were scared that their church would be bombed.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:05.000
But then there was a lot of people that stood up with us.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:16.000
So, as you know, by being a historian that you are, that the civil rights movement here was based on the small people.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:20.000
They have nots, the maids, the garbage workers.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:28.000
We did not have a lot of the professional black people involved because of the fear of losing their jobs.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:34.000
And even my grandmother was a maid.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:50.000
And my grandmother in order to educate my mother and her two other siblings moved into the servant quarters in nickel seals to nurse somebody else's kids in order to educate my mom.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:55.000
And doing the civil rights movement, my grandmother was still a maid.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:04.000
With the nickels and dimes and the sweat and tears.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:08.000
But then those that were committed to the movement were committed.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:12.000
We used to sing a song and go let nobody turn me around.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
And that's what we did.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:19.000
And some of them had to write notes and they put it under our door.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:25.000
The strategy because they didn't want to physically be seen becoming involved in it.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:28.000
But somebody had to stand up.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:30.000
I'm going to ask you two about this.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.000
There's a ball of justice to it too long.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
We're back on after a short pause.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:51.000
I want to ask you two about your mother and the youth councils and all the sort of the whole community of folks who took action.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:56.000
The relationship of that community to the local police department.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.000
We touched on this before we began our filming today.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:10.000
I'm really interested in the role of law enforcement in all of those many, many, many protest moments.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:17.000
Because Oklahoma City unbalanced was relatively free of heavy violence.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:20.000
We had some small incidents of violence.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:35.000
But I think that Oklahoma City consciously made a decision that we did not want to become the focus point of America through the violent aspects of it.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:39.000
And we had a good relationship with the police department.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:44.000
Mom was only arrested 26 times.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.000
She was not beaten up.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:49.000
We were arrested.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:21:07.000
But I think that somewhere along the line that Oklahoma City leadership knew that they were doing a great injustice to all of its residents.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:12.000
And that's why I think that we did not have any violence.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:22.000
Because the good people decided, okay, that I'm protested, I don't know what happened, but we're not going to be a part of it.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:25.000
But then you had some other people that were kind of mean.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:29.000
You got to a chimpanzee on me.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:41.000
And I'm going to ask you just to say that again and explain a little more to Taylor because someone hearing this later might actually not understand what you're being literally truthful about that.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:43.000
No, no, I'm being truthful.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:46.000
We were protesting, thicketing.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:49.000
Now I want my freedom.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:52.000
Welcome around in the man through a chimpanzee on me.

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:54.000
You know, a chimpanzee.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:58.000
I was very small then.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:00.000
I'm a little heavier now.

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:02.000
But I was very small then.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:05.000
The chimpanzee was almost as big as I was.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:08.000
And that was not a good day.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:11.000
There was not a good day.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:14.000
I want to ask a couple of things about your mother.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:16.000
I want to ask you about some of your own.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.000
You were a child really.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:20.000
I'm a young child really.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:21.000
I'm a young child really.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:24.000
A lot of it was.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:34.000
What do you think ultimately your mother's political savvy came from?

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:44.000
And she seemed to be a very set skillful manager of all of the issues that needed to be managed to move forward in a successful way.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:47.000
Did she have innate skills in that area?

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:52.000
Did she have, do you think it was part of what she had studied?

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.000
Did she have an historian?

00:22:54.000 --> 00:23:02.000
Do you think she had key allies who helped her debate those issues and come up with good strategy?

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
I'm interested in your perspective on that.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:07.000
I think it was all of the above.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:10.000
her hobby was to read [the] Congressional Record".

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:13.000
Now who raised the Congress in a record every day?

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:14.000
I mean that's what she did.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:20.000
her hobby was to read [the] Congressional Record".

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:30.000
She knew everybody from everybody here in Oklahoma.

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:33.000
People that could make a difference and people could not.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:40.000
She knew, and she was like the voice of the people when they had problems.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:46.000
The problems became struggles when they were a hope was lost.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:49.000
They came to her.

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:52.000
Nothing just happens.

00:23:52.000 --> 00:24:00.000
I think that she was groomed in history for her day.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:05.000
Did you trouble about your dad in this relation to all of this?

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:11.000
My mother and dad had the worst at early age, right in the midst of it.

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:14.000
There was a lot for him to handle.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:16.000
He was electrician.

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:19.000
He had fun, loving, crazy.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:24.000
You would love to be around him because he's always laughing and joking.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:32.000
But I think that the real pressure that he couldn't handle.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:34.000
That's what I really think.

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:35.000
We never discussed it.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:38.000
He died a few years ago.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:44.000
But it was just I think too much for him to deal with it.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:54.000
Tell me about, do you think back through all of those protests,

00:24:54.000 --> 00:25:01.000
all of those long repeated, difficult protests for years?

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:06.000
What are some of the things that stand out in your memories,

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:09.000
the most important things to tell someone about all of that?

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:11.000
So they understand the essence of it.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:16.000
If it can be explained in any short hand way, I'm not sure if it can.

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:22.000
It can be every Saturday of my young life,

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:27.000
it was spent protesting.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:33.000
We did not have the joys of going to amusement parks

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:36.000
because they were not open to us.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:39.000
And even after they became open,

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:42.000
most of the young people that participated in the cities

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:48.000
did not have the money to even attend the amusement parks.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:56.000
The closeness of the young people that participated in the movement,

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:00.000
throughout not discipline, but throughout this nation,

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:05.000
is one that you can't really understand unless you were there.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:09.000
We celebrated our 50th-anniversary commemoration of the Aug 19, 1958 OKC Katz sit-in

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:12.000
and young people came from all over the United States

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:15.000
to be a part, standard room only.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:19.000
Oh yeah, and they started telling about their experiences

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:21.000
and what they remember.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:26.000
We made recordings to anything that we can because

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:32.000
I'm so glad that we sat down here in Oklahoma City

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:38.000
because if we had not sat down here in Oklahoma City,

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:45.000
young people throughout this nation would not have stood up.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:48.000
And when we think about it,

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:50.000
it's like a whirlwind effect.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:56.000
And we did not realize the importance of what we were doing.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:59.000
We just wanted to make the social changes here,

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:05.000
but little did we know that we had the whirlwind effect

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:09.000
and change American history.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:14.000
Let me ask about one last major theme.

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:17.000
The 1972 Oklahoma Democratic US Senate primary, the 1970s.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:20.000
And let's see, by 1972, you were about how old?

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:23.000
Oh, I don't know.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:28.000
Every year older than I was.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:31.000
Older than I was.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:34.000
What do you think?

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:38.000
Tell us about your...

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:41.000
That's no small undertaking.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:47.000
And I'm interested to have your recollections about that.

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:50.000
I thought my mom was going crazy.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:52.000
But it was a lot of fun.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:59.000
And I enjoyed joining her on the political campaign

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:03.000
because you can't out debate mom,

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:06.000
because you're not going to outread mom.

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:11.000
And she's going to be totally focused whatever she's discussing.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:15.000
Whether it's the governmental system,

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:17.000
and if you start talking about government,

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:21.000
she's been studying government for the last 50 years,

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.000
or the educational system,

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:25.000
because she taught for 40 years.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:32.000
And she was just well-versed in all the issues.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:35.000
And she would go to the little bity small town.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:38.000
I mean, it's towns that are as big as this couch.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:41.000
No black folks, and would say the same thing

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:43.000
as she traveled throughout the state.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:46.000
And people of all races,

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:49.000
and creeds, and colors,

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:53.000
were surprised that she was doing that,

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:56.000
but they supported her.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:59.000
And I think that she had just a little bit longer,

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:03.000
a little bit more time on a year was different in history,

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:06.000
but she would have elected.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:08.000
She would have made the greatest change

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:11.000
that Oklahoma would have ever seen.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:12.000
You remember primary school?

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:14.000
Oh yeah, we lost.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:16.000
But it's okay.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:20.000
Like she said, that's okay. We tried.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:23.000
Do you know what she told what percent of the vote was?

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:25.000
You know, I sure don't.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:28.000
But surprisingly, there's more than people thought

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:31.000
than she would throughout the state of Oklahoma.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:34.000
But I really, in all honesty, I can't remember right now.

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:37.000
There's been a lot of water under the reels at that time.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:40.000
Did you ever consider taking another way of public office?

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:42.000
No.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:45.000
And I can't answer why.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:48.000
That was her decision.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:51.000
John, this was just a sudden.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:54.000
No fear we're rolling.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:57.000
We're back on after short break.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:00.000
And to conclude today,

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:03.000
we're going to talk a little bit about the sanitation workers strike

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:08.000
in the city in I think summer 68.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:12.000
And your mother served a spokesperson.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:20.000
And can you share some recollections about that episode?

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:29.000
The sanitation workers represented a segment of our community.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:36.000
They were overworked and underpaid.

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:42.000
I often wondered why she was selected as a spokesperson.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:48.000
And I asked some of the sanitation workers why she was selected.

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:52.000
And they, I was told that she understood the problem.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:57.000
She would be honest and she was a woman of integrity.

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:04.000
And if she said something, she would stand back and fight to the end.

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:06.000
And many times during the sanitation strike,

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:09.000
I think they thought the end was coming too.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:13.000
Because on that 1969 Oklahoma City Sanitation Workers Strike,

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:18.000
the Oklahoma City has never seen anything like it did that day.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:23.000
But it helped change the city.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:26.000
It helped change it because I think

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:33.000
that somewhere we started to understand that so goes one of us,

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:36.000
so goes all of us.

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:39.000
And if you fail, I fail.

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:41.000
And if I fail, you fail.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:44.000
We're all in this part together.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:50.000
The other thing is that I think the mom represented people

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:55.000
that just couldn't represent themselves.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:32:02.000
You asked me if she was your friend, not that I know of.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:06.000
And she taught me this.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:08.000
And she would say to me every day,

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:10.000
first of all, she would say,

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.000
when she would wake me up in the mornings,

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:13.000
she would say,

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:16.000
do you want to continue your education today?

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:18.000
That's number one.

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:21.000
And even then, she would say,

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:25.000
we were complaining about anything.

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:30.000
She would always have made us learn this.

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:35.000
To believe in the rain when the rain didn't fall,

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:39.000
and to believe in the sun when the sun didn't shine,

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:42.000
and believe in a God that you've never seen.

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:45.000
That's who Clara Luperes.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:47.000
So, thank you so much for sharing.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:49.000
I'm pretty up to you with us today.

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:51.000
Welcome to Mexico, Oklahoma City.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:54.000
We're very pleased to have talked to you about the mother

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:56.000
and yourself and your family.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:58.000
Please context, thank you.

00:32:58.000 --> 00:32:59.000
You're welcome.

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:02.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:06.000
and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:08.000
and Culture.
